Virtual -- tThe Fable of the Bees in Contemporary Penal Law -- tSummons, Prophecies, Possession and Madness: Intersections of Law and Magic in Jonathan Strange & Mr Norrell -- tAn Invented Executive: The Ministry of Magic in Harry Potter -- tLaw and Magic: King Arthur and the Making of a Myth -- tContributors -- tSubject index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe latest development concerning the metaphorical use of the fairy tale is the legal perspective. The law had and has recourse to fairy tales in order to speak of the nomos and its subversion, of the politically correct and of the various means that have been used to enforce the law. Fairy tales are a fundamental tool to examine legal procedures and structures in their many failings and errors. Therefore, we have privileged the term "fables" of the law just to stress the ethical perspective: they are moral parables that often speak of justice miscarried and justice sought.Law and jurists are creators of "fables" on the view that law is born out of the facts (ex facto ius oritur) so that there is a need for narrative coherence both on the level of the case and the level of legislation (or turned the other way around: what does it mean if no such coherence is found?). This is especially of interest given the influx of all kinds of new technologies that are "fabulous" in themselves and hard to incorporate in traditional doctrinal schemes and thus in the construction of a new reality.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aLawxFolklore. 0aTales. 4aFabel. 4aLiteratur. 4aMärchen. 4aRecht. 7aLAW / General.2bisacsh  aLaw.  afables.  afairy tales.  aliterature.1 aAdami, Valentina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBal